<subSubSection pageId="90" pageNumber="368" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="368" targetBox="[2407,2411,2669,2694]" targetPageId="90">
<paragraph blockId="90.[2065,2662,1759,2182]" pageId="90" pageNumber="368">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2071,2247,1991,2024]" pageId="90" pageNumber="368">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from isolated records in SW Nicaragua and WC Costa Rica.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="90" pageNumber="368" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="90.[2065,2662,1759,2182]" pageId="90" pageNumber="368">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2071,2324,2109,2142]" pageId="90" pageNumber="368">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 71-72, tail 96-101 mm, ear 13 mm, hindfoot 18 mm;
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="90.[1457,2664,2188,2694]" pageId="90" pageNumber="368">
for two individuals from the type locality. No specific data are available for body weight. The Nicaraguan Harvest Mouse is small; dorsum is buffy brown, infused with ocherous hairs; sides are ocherous; and venter is white. Hindfoot has characteristic wedgeshaped dusky area that extends to bases of toes. Tail is long relative to head-body length. Skull resembles that of the Short-nosed Harvest Mouse (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Goodwin" authorityYear="1943" box="[2357,2537,2345,2378]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Reithrodontomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="90" pageNumber="368" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brevirostris">R. brevirostris</taxonomicName>
), but it is longer and less inflated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1459,2492,2424,2457]" pageId="90" pageNumber="368" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="90.[1457,2664,2188,2694]" box="[1459,2492,2424,2457]" pageId="90" pageNumber="368">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1459,1570,2424,2457]" pageId="90" pageNumber="368">Habitat.</emphasis>
